03888nam a22005655i 9780822376996DE-B159720201125033335.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||201125t20142014ncu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808223769967 a10.1515/97808223769962doi  a(DE-B1597)553603  a(OCoLC)873034924  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ancucUS-NC 4aHQ77.95.V4bO24 2014 7aSOC0320002bisacsh04a306.76/82231 aOchoa, Marcia, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aQueen for a Day :bTransformistas, Beauty Queens, and the Performance of Femininity in Venezuela /cMarcia Ochoa. 1aDurham : bDuke University Press, c[2014] 4cÂ©2014  a1 online resource (296 p.) :b20 photographs, 1 map  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aPerverse Modernities: A Series Edited by Jack Halberstam and Lisa Lowe00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroducing . . . the Queen -- tPART I. On the (Trans)National -- t1. Belleza Venezolana -- t2. La Moda Nace en Paris y Muere en Caracas -- tPART II. On the Runway, on the Street -- t3. La Reina de la Noche -- t4. Pasarelas y Perolones -- tPART III. On the Body -- t5. Sacar el Cuerpo -- t6. Spectacular Femininities -- tEPILOGUE. Democracy and Melodrama -- tNotes -- tReferences -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aQueen for a Day connects the logic of Venezuelan modernity with the production of a national femininity. In this ethnography, Marcia Ochoa considers how femininities are produced, performed, and consumed in the mass-media spectacles of international beauty pageants, on the runways of the Miss Venezuela contest, on the well-traveled Caracas avenue where transgender women (transformistas) project themselves into the urban imaginary, and on the bodies of both transformistas and beauty pageant contestants (misses). Placing transformistas and misses in the same analytic frame enables Ochoa to delve deeply into complex questions of media and spectacle, gender and sexuality, race and class, and self-fashioning and identity in Venezuela.Beauty pageants play an outsized role in Venezuela. The country has won more international beauty contests than any other. The femininity performed by Venezuelan women in high-profile, widely viewed pageants defines a kind of national femininity. Ochoa argues that as transformistas and misses work to achieve the bodies, clothing and makeup styles, and postures and gestures of this national femininity, they come to embody Venezuelan modernity.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 25. Nov 2020) 0aBeauty contestantszVenezuela. 0aFemininityzVenezuela. 0aTranssexualszVenezuela. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Gender Studies.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDUK eBook-Package 2014-2015z978311071182040uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780822376996zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780822376996423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780822376996.jpg  a978-3-11-071182-0  DUK eBook-Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aEBA_DUK_ALL  aEBA_DUK_EALL  aEBA_DUK_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles